{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529874"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.11,0.78,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104551"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4606"},{"type":"tags","id":"5846"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17186"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104551"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old man is admitted to the surgical ward with acute cholecystitis. An emergency call is made for new-onset tachypnoea. He was admitted two days ago with fever and right upper quadrant pain, and is being managed non-surgically due to his age and comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, congestive heart failure, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and ischaemic heart disease. His regular medications include salbutamol inhaler, tiotropium inhaler, metformin, empagliflozin, ramipril, metoprolol, frusemide, atorvastatin, and aspirin. Most of his regular medications are being withheld during his acute illness. He is receiving regular intravenous ceftriaxone and metronidazole, as well as maintenance and supplementary intravenous fluids (total 3 L in the past 24 hours).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 92% on room air and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals mild bilateral wheeze. His abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant with guarding. There is no peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA venous blood gas shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.30 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E: 32 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO\u003Csub\u003E3\u003C/sub\u003E: 15 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate: 4.0 mmol/L (0.5-1.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute myocardial infarction","COPD exacerbation","Sepsis","Pulmonary oedema","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis elderly patient, admitted with acute cholecystitis and multiple comorbidities, has developed sudden breathlessness along with signs of systemic inflammatory response syndrome, including tachycardia, tachypnoea, and fever. These findings, in the context of a known infection (cholecystitis), are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esepsis\u003C/strong\u003E. The venous blood gas further supports this, showing metabolic acidosis with an elevated lactate, indicating tissue hypoperfusion and organ dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECOPD exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility given the patient\u0027s history and the presence of wheeze on auscultation. However, the hypotension and metabolic acidosis with hypocapnia are not typical features of a COPD exacerbation alone and suggest a more systemic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E due to acute decompensation of the patient\u0027s congestive heart failure could cause breathlessness. However, the absence of peripheral oedema, the presence of high fever, and the lack of crackles on auscultation make this diagnosis less likely. Additionally, the metabolic acidosis with elevated lactate is more suggestive of sepsis than heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E is always a consideration in an elderly patient with risk factors presenting with breathlessness. However, the absence of chest pain and the presence of high fever make acute myocardial infarction less likely in this scenario. While acute myocardial infarction can cause metabolic acidosis and elevated lactate, the overall clinical picture is more consistent with sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the respiratory symptoms and fever. However, the abdominal tenderness and the context of recent admission for cholecystitis make sepsis from an abdominal source more likely than a new pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESepsis is a life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection. In this case, the patient\u0027s acute cholecystitis has likely progressed to sepsis, as evidenced by the new onset of tachypnoea, tachycardia, fever, hypotension, and metabolic acidosis with elevated lactate. The patient\u0027s advanced age and multiple comorbidities increase his risk for developing sepsis. Early recognition and prompt management of sepsis, including fluid resuscitation, blood cultures, and broad-spectrum antibiotics, are crucial to improve outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tachypnoea, tachycardia, and fever in a patient with known infection should raise suspicion for sepsis.","Early recognition and management of sepsis is crucial to improve patient outcomes.","Metabolic acidosis with elevated lactate is a common finding in sepsis and indicates tissue hypoperfusion."],"references":["Bullock B, Benham MD. Bacterial Sepsis. [Updated 2023 May 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537054/","Auda A, Al Abdullah R, Khalid MO, Alrasheed WY, Alsulaiman SA, Almulhem FT, Almaideni MF, Alhikan A. Acute Cholecystitis Presenting With Septic Shock as the First Presentation in an Elderly Patient. Cureus. 2022 Jan 6;14(1):e20981. doi: 10.7759/cureus.20981. PMID: 35004094; PMCID: PMC8733902.","Jarczak D, Kluge S, Nierhaus A. Sepsis-Pathophysiology and Therapeutic Concepts. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 May 14;8:628302. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.628302. PMID: 34055825; PMCID: PMC8160230."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T15:08:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T15:08:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7166"}},